10-23-80

The salvator salvandus --who is both Savior and ones real Self-- speaks cryptic clues in a still small inner voice in the night, recalling Self to Self, to re-collect it. It can only be heard when and where there is exact silence. It reminds the splintered, empty Self as to who it is, where it is, the true conditions under which it exists in subjugation and forgetfulness; cryptic clues by it to itself. That stir its memory. The name of the true Self, the Savior is -- unity. The implosion, reversal of the original explosion. The splintered Self at first does not recognize the voice and does not understand the clues. Then by degrees the Self understands the clues and recognizes the voice as the Savior's. Finally the Self recognizes the voice as its own voice (salvator salvandus) and understands the clues; is caused to remember, and, by figuring out the clues itself, understands its true condition. That it Fell; where it is now and its dasein; and that it has now been "adopted," i.e. saved. Taken back up: restored out of the spatiotemporal bondage (forfeiture). (To the Other.) It is as in VR: when Zina Pallas the loving twin removes her last mask or veil and reveals her identity, Emmanuel realizes, "It is myself. The lost part of myself, guiding me and speaking to me." Splintering (explosion) is the Fall. Recollection (re-collection) (and recognition of the other as the missing parts of Self) is the restoration. What was alien and outside and an it is familiar and inside and a Thou. This whole process of re-collection begins by a re-cognition of something outside that is suddenly and correctly seen to be familiar; this causes anamnesis, re-collection. A part of the alien other is neither alien nor other; it is familiar and it is ones. It does not stand opposed to the self as the thing, the alien, the other. All this Heidegger ontology is okay, but the missing other part (half?) of myself was literally thousands of years and thousands of miles away, so its return was a supernatural event lifting me out of time and space... into a higher realm: that of before the Fall, phylogenically. Not merely ontogenically. Also I doubt if Heidegger realized that to re-collect the Self the salvator salvandus would speak in a still small voice to the remaining splinter of the Self, speaking necessarily cryptic clues --necessarily, because the remaining Self splinter must fit the pieces together and so truly understand, not just be told).


